  </CTABox>

  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Getting the Alien Registration Card</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The ARC is essential for daily life in Korea—banking, phone contracts, many services require it. Apply within 90 days of arrival.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Language Barriers</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While major areas have English, daily life is easier with basic Korean. Apps like Papago (translation) and Naver Maps are essential.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Flexible Program Rules</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Korea's Workcation visa is newer and requirements may be strictly interpreted. Have all documentation ready and verify current requirements.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Housing Deposits</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Korean rentals traditionally require large deposits (jeonse or high wolse deposits). Factor this into your budget or use nomad-friendly housing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Using Korean Apps</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Korea runs on Korean apps: KakaoTalk (messaging), Naver Maps (better than Google in Korea), Coupang (delivery). Download and set up before arrival.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in South Korea -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in South Korea</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      South Korea has excellent healthcare—efficient, technologically advanced, and affordable by developed country standards. Korean hospitals are among the best in the world.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Facilities</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Asan Medical Center</strong> - Seoul, one of Asia's largest hospitals</li>
      <li><strong>Samsung Medical Center</strong> - Seoul, world-class facility</li>
      <li><strong>Severance Hospital (Yonsei)</strong> - Seoul, top-ranked teaching hospital</li>
      <li><strong>Seoul National University Hospital</strong> - Leading public hospital</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Medical Tourism Hub</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Korea is a major medical tourism destination, especially for cosmetic surgery, dental work, and health checkups. English-speaking international clinics cater to foreigners.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> $30-50</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $50-100</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency room:</strong> $100-300</li>
      <li><strong>Dental cleaning:</strong> $30-60</li>
      <li><strong>MRI:</strong> $300-500 (vs $1,000-3,000 in US)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How established is Korea's Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Korea's Workcation visa launched in 2023 and is still evolving. It may be offered through bilateral agreements or pilot programs. Check with your local Korean embassy for current availability and requirements for your nationality.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I access Korean National Health Insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 6 months of residence with proper visa status, you typically become eligible for NHIS. It costs approximately $100-150/month and covers about 70% of medical costs. Until then, use international health insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Korean?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not required, but helpful. Seoul and major cities have English signage and English-speaking services at major hospitals. Daily life is easier with basic Korean, and translation apps (Papago, Google Translate) are essential.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How fast is the internet really?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Korea has the world's fastest average internet speeds—consistently over 200 Mbps, with 5G widely available. Cafes, coworking spaces, and even public transport have excellent wifi. Internet is never an issue.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the best area for digital nomads in Seoul?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Hongdae (young, creative), Gangnam (corporate, upscale), Itaewon (international, diverse), and Seongsu (Brooklyn-like, trendy) are popular. Busan offers beach lifestyle and lower costs. Consider your priorities: nightlife, cafes, quiet, or international community.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about the 90-day visa-free entry?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Many nationalities can enter Korea visa-free for up to 90 days. This is for tourism, not work. While enforcement on remote work is minimal, the Workcation visa provides legal status. For stays over 90 days, you need proper visa status.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      South Korea offers a unique digital nomad experience: world's fastest internet, exceptional healthcare, remarkable safety, and deep cultural immersion. For those interested in K-culture or wanting a highly efficient, tech-forward base in Asia, Korea is compelling.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The main considerations are the newer visa program (verify current requirements), language barriers outside major areas, and moderate-to-high living costs in Seoul. Korean winters are also quite cold.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For nomads who value infrastructure, safety, and want to experience one of Asia's most dynamic countries, Korea delivers. The combination of tradition and hyper-modernity creates a fascinating environment for living and working.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        South Korea's Workcation visa offers access to world-class internet, healthcare, and safety in a culturally rich environment. Verify current requirements with your Korean embassy, get proper insurance, and prepare for an exceptional experience in one of Asia's most innovative countries.
